The public religion at Rome in Ovid's day had lost all meaning, and become purely formal. Accordingly the poet, who was, and knew himself to be, representative of his time in the fullest degree, portrays gods and goddesses as swayed by all the most unworthy passions os human bcings, in fact, as merely reflecting the manners and morals os the sashionable society of his own day.
